459
00:37:14,230 --> 00:37:18,250
I thought, "How can they
replace the irreplaceable

460
00:37:18,250 --> 00:37:22,710
No-one would have accepted
another actor playing Compo,

461
00:37:22,710 --> 00:37:29,230
but Alan and Roy
came up with the idea
of having Bill's real-life son Tom

462
00:37:29,230 --> 00:37:31,970
playing Compo's long-lost son Tom.

463
00:37:31,970 --> 00:37:35,510
I'm looking for
a Mr William Simmonite.

464
00:37:35,510 --> 00:37:38,990
Now's your chance. Tell him.

465
00:37:40,530 --> 00:37:42,550
Father!

466
00:37:42,550 --> 00:37:45,250
Oh, no! Not me!

467
00:37:45,250 --> 00:37:49,930
'The problem was solved!
We had a link with dear old Bill.'

468
00:37:49,930 --> 00:37:52,470
I recognise the ears!

469
00:37:54,650 --> 00:37:56,690
Daddy!

470
00:37:56,690 --> 00:38:00,410
I'm not your daddy.
I'm a retired policeman!

471
00:38:00,410 --> 00:38:05,130
Some years ago, Stephen Lewis
joined for one episode

472
00:38:05,130 --> 00:38:07,970
to play a man in hospital,

473
00:38:07,970 --> 00:38:12,730
but he was so well liked
that it was decided, eventually,

474
00:38:12,730 --> 00:38:15,810
to keep him on as a regular.

475
00:38:15,810 --> 00:38:19,950
'He's provided hours
and hours of unsmiling pleasure.'

476
00:38:19,950 --> 00:38:24,910
I want you to judge the performance.
See if you can see the lips moving.

477
00:38:26,670 --> 00:38:32,270
My name is Waldo. A funny thing
happened on the way to the kennel.

478
00:38:35,770 --> 00:38:38,070
What are you waiting for?

479
00:38:38,070 --> 00:38:42,430
To hear what the funny thing was
on the way to the kennel.

480
00:38:42,430 --> 00:38:46,150
I haven't written it yet!
Did my lips move?

481
00:38:46,150 --> 00:38:50,030
Yes! He was moving his lips
all the time.

482
00:38:50,030 --> 00:38:53,750
Not him, me!
Did you see MY lips move?

483
00:38:53,750 --> 00:38:58,870
I wasn't watching your lips.
HE was the one that was speaking!

484
00:38:58,870 --> 00:39:03,850
And a few years earlier, Billy
Hardcastle had joined our company.

485
00:39:03,850 --> 00:39:11,150
'Billy Hardcastle,
distant relative of Robin Hood,
played by Keith Clifford.'

486
00:39:11,150 --> 00:39:14,250
It will penetrate steel, will this.

487
00:39:18,210 --> 00:39:23,290
I'm really going to enjoy this.
Somebody keep that sheriff quiet!

488
00:39:36,490 --> 00:39:39,030
On my sitcoms, even though now

489
00:39:39,030 --> 00:39:42,550
we do Summer Wine
entirely all on film,

490
00:39:42,550 --> 00:39:47,810
we still show that finished film
to an invited audience

491
00:39:47,810 --> 00:39:50,890
and we record their laughter.

492
00:39:52,290 --> 00:39:58,830
The BBC go to
some considerable trouble to ensure
the audience have a good night out.

493
00:39:58,830 --> 00:40:03,170
# U make my life complete
V means you're VERY sweet

494
00:40:03,170 --> 00:40:05,310
# W-X-Y-Z... #

495
00:40:05,310 --> 00:40:10,190
I don't like to see the shows going
out without hearing any laughter.

496
00:40:10,190 --> 00:40:13,870
It alters the atmosphere
completely.

497
00:40:13,870 --> 00:40:19,710
I don't want canned laughter, but
I don't want no laughter at all.

498
00:40:19,710 --> 00:40:24,870
I enjoyed it. People don't think it
is for young people. I think it is.

499
00:40:24,870 --> 00:40:30,390
It's the best show on the air!
Worth the licence fee.

500
00:40:30,390 --> 00:40:34,370
Wonderful. It really was...
Wonderful!

501
00:40:34,370 --> 00:40:37,050
And what of the future?

502
00:40:37,050 --> 00:40:44,310
Who would have thought that we
would have happened upon a Chinese
electrical engineer from Hull?!

503
00:40:44,310 --> 00:40:47,690
What's your name?
It's on the van.

504
00:40:48,870 --> 00:40:51,670
Electrical?!
Entwistle!

505
00:40:51,670 --> 00:40:55,470
Don't think I'm being nosey,
just because I am,

506
00:40:55,470 --> 00:40:59,010
but how come
you've got a name like Entwistle?

507
00:40:59,010 --> 00:41:05,110
I changed my name, didn't I?
From McIntyre. I was forever
being mistaken for a Scot!

508
00:41:05,110 --> 00:41:08,830
What are you, then?
A Yorkshireman, what else?!

509
00:41:09,970 --> 00:41:14,010
TRANSLATION:

510
00:41:30,850 --> 00:41:34,550
Now I will interpret.

511
00:41:34,550 --> 00:41:39,090
I am delighted to be doing
Last Of The Summer Wine.

512
00:41:39,090 --> 00:41:42,150
And what of poor old Nora Batty?

513
00:41:42,150 --> 00:41:46,510
She never thought
she'd wake up one morning

514
00:41:46,510 --> 00:41:51,350
and find an Alvin living next door
to her in Compo's old house.

515
00:41:51,350 --> 00:41:55,150
What's he smiling at?
You do me good, love.

516
00:41:55,150 --> 00:42:00,230
Reminds me I used to be married to
one of them. Can't believe me luck!

517
00:42:00,230 --> 00:42:04,370
I have watched
Last Of The Summer Wine,

518
00:42:04,370 --> 00:42:06,830
man and boy, for 30 years.

519
00:42:08,030 --> 00:42:13,630
It is a great pleasure and privilege
to be asked to join the company,

520
00:42:13,630 --> 00:42:18,290
because many of the actors
are old colleagues and friends.

521
00:42:18,290 --> 00:42:24,530
But I have to tell you
that for many years I had
a dragon of a wife called Mildred.

522
00:42:24,530 --> 00:42:31,830
It is with great trepidation that
I am going to have to face up to
an even bigger dragon in Nora Batty.

523
00:42:35,070 --> 00:42:40,870
Just in time for tea, ladies!
You'll have us all on fire.

524
00:42:40,870 --> 00:42:44,670
I don't think you'd burn,
old asbestos breeches!

525
00:42:47,530 --> 00:42:50,190
If it begins to slide,

526
00:42:50,190 --> 00:42:54,590
then it wants burying peacefully,
with great fondness,

527
00:42:54,590 --> 00:42:58,250
but if the audience
is still out there,

528
00:42:58,250 --> 00:43:00,750
I'd love to do another one.

529
